postcontent:
This Smith is in good condition with no scratches or dings. I have included a write-up of the model 65-3. 

The Smith and Wesson model 65 revolver was introduced in 1973. It was one of several .357 magnum variations of the extremely popular model 10. It is built on the medium sized K frame, making it one of Smith and Wesson's medium-weight models. 

The model 65 was produced from 1973 to 1999, then some minor changes were made. It continued to be produced until 2004. 

The model 65 was always a popular gun with law enforcement officers, as it could handle full-power .357 magnum or .38 +P loads without a problem, and had very good balance and handling characteristics.

The model 65 is no longer produced, but can be readily found used or as new in box. While it's not a collectors item (yet), it is a very desirable revolver.

For sale is a beautiful Norinco NHM-91 AK-47 chambered in 7.62x39mm. This rifle is in excellent condition inside and out. There is no rust, pitting, or wear on any steel, and the furniture is in great shape with the exception of two blemishes on the foregrip. Comes with the 75 round drum magazine pictured.

Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches. Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or Chinese-made AKM, resulting in increased rigidity, heavier weight, and improved overall accuracy. The longer, heavier barrel reduces shot dispersion and gives the NHM-91 a longer sight radius, again resulting in improved accuracy over the typical semi-auto AKM. Trigger pull weight is also lighter than other AK designs, and some users report the rifle capable of 2-2.5 minutes of angle accuracy or better with factory 7.62x39mm ammunition.

title: For Sale:  LaserAim pistol with original case, 10mm and .45ACP barrels. Rare!
postcontent:
This is a pistol I'm posting for an older neighbor of mine who's not very familiar with Armslist, so if you have any questions it might take me a bit to get back to you as I have to go through him. 

This pistol was produced sometime in the mid-late 1990s in Little Rock, AR by the LaserAim company to serve as a dedicated host for their laser module products. From what I can tell it's a fairly rare gun, and it seems to be well made. The grip is very similar in shape to a CZ or Tanfoglio, but is much more slim due to being a single-stack. Overall the design of the gun seems to be heavily inspired by but not necessarily an exact clone of the 1911, although it does take 1911 mags. It comes with the original laser module but according to the owner it no longer works, this was apparently not uncommon judging by posts I've found from other owners of this model handgun.

This comes with two 7" 10mm and .45ACP barrels, both of which were cut with compensator ports at the factory. Owner is looking for cash, he's unfortunately got no use for trades. This would be a great piece for collectors of 10mm pistols or uncommon handguns.
